7.1 Introduction

“EDA” 1. Generate questions about your data.
2. Search for answers by visualising, transforming, and modelling your data.
3. Use what you learn to refine your questions and/or generate new questions.

“state of mind”

7.2 Questions

Two questions that will always be useful: 1. What type of variation occurs within my variables?
2. What type of covariation occurs between my variables?

variable – a quantity, quality, or property you can measure value – the state of a variable when you measure it (may change from measurement to measurement) observation - set of measurements made under similar conditions tabular data – a set of values, each associated with a variable and an observation

7.3 Variation

variation - the tendency of the values of a variable to change from measurement to measurement ** every ** measurement will include a small amount of error in continuous variables categorical variables will vary across different subjects ### 7.3.1 Visualizing distributions
categorical – can only take one of a small set of variables; usually factors or character vectors bar chart or dplyr::count()

continuous – can take any of an infinite set of ordered values histogram set intervals in a histogram with binwidth argument explore a variety of binwidths when working with histograms geom_freqpoly() does the same calculation by uses lines ### 7.3.2 Typical values What values are the most common? Why?
What values are rare? Why? Does that match your expectations?
Can you see any unusual patterns? What might explain them?

If there are clusters of similar values in data == subgroups
How are observations within clusters similar to each other?
How are observations in separate clusters different from each other?
### 7.3.3 Unusual values outlier – observation that is unusual and doesn’t seem to fit the pattern can be hard to see on graph coord_cartesian() – sets ylim and xlim to zoom in setting with xlim() or ylim() throws out data outside the limits

good practice to repeat your analysis with and without the outliers – minimal effect on the results and can’t figure out why they are > remove them – substantial effect on results -> don’t drop them, figure out what caused them, disclose that you removed them in your writeup

7.5 Covariation

covariation - tendency for the values of two or more variables to vary together in a related way ### 7.5.1 A categorical and continuous variable visualize distribution of a continuous variable broken down by a categorical variable geom_freqpoly() not that useful because height given by count (hides much smaller groups) density – count standardized so that the area under each frequency polygon is one

ggplot(data = diamonds, mapping = aes(x = price, y = ..density..)) + 
  geom_freqpoly(mapping = aes(colour = cut), binwidth = 500)

can be confusing to compare

boxplot - box stretches from the 25th percentile to the 75th percentile (IQR) - line in middle of box displays the median - points are observations more than 1.5 times the IQR from either edge - whisker/line extends from box to farthest non-outlier point in the distribution

reorder(VARIABLE TO BE REORDERED, VARIABLE TO REORDER BY, FUNCTION TO ANALYSE RE-ORDERER)

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = reorder(class, hwy, FUN = median), y = hwy)) +
  geom_boxplot()

coord_flip() flips the boxplot 90degrees

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = reorder(class, hwy, FUN = median), y = hwy)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
   coord_flip()

7.5.1.1

  1. Use what you’ve learned to improve the visualisation of the departure times of cancelled vs. non-cancelled flights. Adjusting geom_freqpoly to display the distribution by density negates the issue of not-many-cancelled flights.
flights %>% 
  mutate(
    cancelled = is.na(dep_time),
    sched_hour = sched_dep_time %/% 100,
    sched_min = sched_dep_time %% 100,
    sched_dep_time = sched_hour + sched_min / 60
  ) %>%
   ggplot(mapping = aes(x = sched_dep_time)) +
   geom_freqpoly(aes(y = ..density.., color = cancelled, binwidth = 1/4))

The violin plots are probably the best for comparing the overall shape of the distributions among the other viarable. The faceted histogram gives each shapes distribution and also gives you an idea of the counts. The freqpoly is the best for comparing specific regions.

7.5.2 Two categorical variables

count the number of observations in each combination geom_count() – displays a circle whose size represents the count OR compute the count with dplyr and visualized with geom_tile

if categorical variables unordered, seriation package simultaneously reorders rows and columns d3heatmap or heatmaply packages create interactive plots

7.5.3 Two continuous variables

SCATTERPLOTS overplotting – use alpha to add transparency bin in two dimensions

geom_bin2d()[rectange] and geom_hex()[hexagonal bins] divide coordinate plan into 2d bins and use a fill color to display how many points

alternatively, bin one of the continuous variables and use a continuous-categorical visualization tool cut_width(VARIABLE, BINWIDTH)

ggplot(data = diamonds, mapping = aes(x = carat, y = price)) + 
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(group = cut_width(carat, 0.1, varwidth = TRUE)))

cut_number(variable, number of points) displays about the same number of points in each bin

7.6 Patterns and models

variation creates uncertainty; covariation reduces it if two variables covary, you can use one to make predictions about the second not all covarying variables have a causal relationship
